{"key":"processedPost-8969038","value":{"id":8969038,"first":8968728,"last":8970853,"when":1222125234,"utime":"09/23/08 02:13 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />Stick with rye grain for substrate for spawn running and Peat/verm or enriched equine dung for casing.</blockquote><br />This is why so many people mess up their grows.&nbsp; Horse manure is NOT a casing, and too many people around here are not familiar with the nomenclature of cultivation.<br />Peat/verm is used as a casing layer, but is entirely optional when you've spawned to a bulk substrate.&nbsp; The only time you'd really need a casing layer with cubensis is if you wanted to fruit from straight rye berries or wbs.&nbsp; In that case, you'd lay the grains out in a tray, and cover with 1/2\" of pasteurized casing material.<br />A substrate is what you actually grow the mushrooms on.&nbsp; Items like straw, manure, worm castings, coir, etc., are all examples of substrate.&nbsp; When using these for substrate, you inoculate it with your fully colonized pf cakes or rye grains, which are your <i>spawn</i>.<br />When using a bulk substrate to grow cubensis, a casing layer is optional, and quite frankly in my experience, you'll do as well without a casing by maintaining proper fruiting parameters.<br />RR","title":"Re: unclear of substrate/casing"}}